SIMPLE: ordinal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ordinal
<hw>Or"di*nal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ordinalis</ets>, fr. <ets>ordo</ets>, <ets>ordinis</ets>, order.
See <er>Order</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Indicating order or
succession; <as>as, the <ex>ordinal</ex> numbers, first, second, third,
etc.</as> Contrasted to <contr>cardinal</contr>. </def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to an order.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ordinal
<hw>Or"di*nal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A word or number
denoting order or succession.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Ch. of Eng.)</fld> <def>The book of forms for
making, ordaining, and consecrating bishops, priests, and
deacons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A book containing the rubrics
of the Mass.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>ordinale</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinalism</ent>⟦br⟧
